data.snippet:
# Pranjal Chalise

### Peer Career Advisor

Pranjal Chalise is a Software Engineer at Microsoft since June 2025, specializing in CoreAI. Concurrently, Pranjal serves as a Peer Career Advisor and a Peer Tutor in both the Math and Computer Science Departments at Amherst College, providing support for students in academic and professional development. Pranjal's prior experience includes working as an AI/ML Fellow and Software Engineer at Microsoft in 2024, and holding various roles at Amherst College such as Math & Stats Student Steering Committee Fellow and IT Specialist. Additionally, Pranjal contributed as a Research Assistant and Research Scholar at Incubate Nepal and is pursuing a Bachelor of Arts in Computer Science and Mathematics at Amherst College, expected to graduate in May 2026. It distribution is in the mid-central, mid-back and low-back regions. The scatter plot also reveals the levels of stability of the Baram vowels. [i], [u] and [a] are the most stable vowels and show the nature of the quantal vowels. Relatively [e] and [o] are stable but not as stable as the previous three. In comparison, [e] is more stable than [o].Of all, […ô]is the most unstable vowel and it fluctuates in the wide area of central-back and mid-low regions.
